Sub-Saharan African Stocks: Kenya Commercial and Mauritius Commercial Move

-- B y   C h r i s   K a y
-- 
2011-04-12T15:41:29Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-12/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenya-commercial-mauritius-commercial-move.html
The Ghana Stock Exchange Composite
Index dropped for a third day, falling 0.3 percent to 1,046.76
by the 3 p.m. close in Accra, the lowest since March 3.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index fell for the first day in five,
declining 0.1 percent to 2,038.03 at the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port
Louis . Kenya’s All-Share Index rose for a third day, adding 0.1
percent to 75.11 by the 3 p.m. close in Nairobi. The Nigerian
Stock Exchange All-Share Index added less than 0.1 percent to
24,681.99 by 2:30 p.m. close in Lagos, according to an e-mailed
statement from the bourse.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
slumped for the first day in 3, losing 2.3 percent to 877.19 by
the 4 p.m. close in Windhoek.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.        Kenya Commercial Bank Ltd. (KNCB)  , the nation’s biggest
lender by outlets, gained for a fourth day, climbing 25 cents,
or 1 percent, to 26 shillings after the Nairobi-based Business
Daily reported the company plans to invest 1.9 billion shillings
($22.6 million) in expansion.  Mauritius Commercial Bank (MCB)  , the India Ocean island
nation’s largest lender by market value, declined for the first
day in four, falling 1 rupee, or 0.6 percent, to 175 rupees,
after l’Express reported the bank aims to re-acquire all the
shares in Fincorp Investment Co., in which it owns a 54 percent
stake. The newspaper didn’t say where it got the information.
MCB declined to comment when contacted by Bloomberg News.  Sterling Bank (STERLNBA)  Plc, a Nigerian lender, fell 11
kobo, or 4.8 percent, to 2.19 naira, the most in a month after
the bank didn’t declare a dividend or issue bonus shares after
turning to profit last year.  “The results are good, but investors want compensation for
their investments,” David Adonri, chief executive officer of
Lagos-based Lambeth Trust and Investment Co., said by phone
today. “Investors are reacting to the non-declaration of
dividend or bonus.”  To contact the reporter on this story:
